explanation:
To determine whether any statements in OS_FDGetInfo constitute dead code (i.e. are executed but could be removed without changing program behaviour) the next analyzer needs the semantics, side-effects and possible return/control-flow behaviors of the following symbols:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro that validates fd_prop; it may return, abort, or log. Knowing its behavior is necessary to see if any subsequent statements are guaranteed to execute or are unreachable/conditional at call time.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Determines whether the if-block (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) can be entered. Its possible return values and side-effects (e.g. token initialization) are crucial to decide if the body is ever executed in practice.

- OS_SUCCESS: The value tested by the if. Needed to interpret return_code outcomes from OS_ObjectIdGetById.

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The object type passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; influences which lookup path and thus which return behavior (affects reachability of the success path).

- OS_object_token_t: Type and semantics of the token output by OS_ObjectIdGetById (e.g. whether it must be released). This affects whether OS_ObjectIdRelease is necessary (removal might change behaviour).

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Appears via macros/utility used to map token -> table index. Understanding it shows whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET can always succeed or have side-effects (affects whether record access is meaningful).

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro/function used to obtain the record from OS_global_stream_table and token. Its implementation and side-effects determine whether the record pointer read is meaningful or if the macro might perform additional work (affects dead-code judgment for the block that uses the record).

- OS_global_stream_table: The table from which the record is fetched. Its declaration/layout affects whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET can ever yield a useful record for a given token/id (informs reachability and effect of the code using record).

- OS_common_record_t: Structure type for record (fields name_entry and creator). Needed to know whether accesses record->name_entry and record->creator are reading relevant state or are no-ops / undefined.

- OS_file_prop_t: Structure type for fd_prop (fields Path, User, IsValid). Needed to determine whether memset and the subsequent assignments modify observable program state; this is needed to assess whether those writes are removable without effect.

- memset: Called to zero fd_prop. Knowing it is the standard initializer and whether it has side-effects (or is redundant) is necessary to assess if removing it would change behaviour.

- strncpy: Copies record->name_entry into fd_prop->Path. Its semantics (particularly whether it can write to fd_prop->Path or truncate) matter to know if the copy is observable or redundant.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token acquired on success. If release has side-effects (resource accounting, unlocking), removing it would change behaviour, so its semantics must be known to judge dead code.

- OS_printf: Included because OS_CHECK_POINTER or other macros may call it for diagnostics; logging side-effects can make code non-dead even if they appear to be only diagnostics.

Collectively, these symbols provide the control-flow (can the success branch be entered?), data-flow (do writes change observable state?), and side-effect information required to decide whether any executed operations in OS_FDGetInfo could safely be removed (i.e. are dead code) under the MISRA definition.
